block subSubContent
	h3
		b The axiom
	p The axiom of infinity states that:
	p $$\exists \mathbb{N} (\varnothing \in \mathbb{N} \land \forall x \in \mathbb{N}((x\lor \{x\})\in \mathbb{N}))$$
	p There exists a set, called the infinite set: \(\exists \mathbb{N} \).
	h3
		b Sequential function
	p Let's define the sequential function:
	p $$s(n):=\{n\lor \{n\}\}$$
	p We can now rewrite the axiom of infinity as:
	p $$\exists \mathbb{N} (\varnothing \in \mathbb{N} \land \forall x \in \mathbb{N}(s(x)\in \mathbb{N}))$$
	h3
		b Zero
	p This set contains the null set: \(\varnothing \in \mathbb{N} \).
	p Zero is defined as the empty set.
	p $$0:=\{\}$$
	p Does \(0\) exist? We know the infinite set exists, and we also know the axiom schema of specification:
	p $$\forall x \forall a \exists s[(P(x)\land x\in a )\leftrightarrow (x\in s)]$$
	p Let's take \(a\) to be the infinite set
	p $$\forall x \exists s[(P(x)\land x\in \mathbb{N} )\leftrightarrow (x\in s)]$$
	p Consider the preterite \(x\ne x\):
	p $$\forall x \exists s[x\ne x\land x\in \mathbb{N} )\leftrightarrow (x\in s)]$$
